<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1294,2041]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,415,1402,1429]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description. Male</emphasis>
. Whole fly as 
<figureCitation box="[589,674,1403,1429]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 70</figureCitation>
. Head as 
<figureCitation box="[789,873,1403,1429]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
, with the frons lacking microtrichia except at its edges. Cheek with 4 bristles and jowl with 2 that are longer and more robust. Postpedicels 
<figureCitation box="[1198,1282,1439,1465]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
, without SPS vesicles but with pale spots. Palps with small pits (
<figureCitation box="[710,793,1475,1501]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
). Three notopleural bristles, with no cleft in front of these, and mesopleuron bare 
<figureCitation box="[408,491,1511,1537]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
. Scutellum with an anterior pair of hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown and venter gray, the latter with hairs on segments 5 and6 only (
<figureCitation box="[1032,1117,1547,1573]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
). Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Figs 74 &amp; 75</figureCitation>
. Legs brown. Fore tarsus (
<figureCitation box="[486,568,1583,1610]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 76</figureCitation>
) with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and 5 clearly longer than 4. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.6 times its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur longer than those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation box="[659,743,1655,1681]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 77</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia with about 20 weakly differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[989,1071,1691,1717]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–78" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1956,1981]" captionTargetBox="[239,1359,461,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[219,1368,453,1931]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 70–78. Megaselia shabestarensis n. sp. male. 70, whole fly; 71, head; 72, postpedicel; 73, side of thorax; 74–75, hypopygium; 76, front tarsus; 77, hind femur; 78, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573384/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[1087,1223,1691,1717]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="1.25" valueMax="1.6" valueMin="0.9">0.9–1.6 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.30–0.35. Costal ratios 7.8–7.9: 1.5–1.7:1. Costal cilia 
<quantity box="[792,892,1727,1753]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="0.09">0.09 mm</quantity>
long. Hair at base of vein 3 
<quantity box="[1211,1311,1727,1753]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="0.02">0.02 mm</quantity>
long. With 2 unequal axillary bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity box="[685,785,1763,1789]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="0.09">0.09 mm</quantity>
long. Vein Sc not reaching vein 1.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1294,2041]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1798,1825]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key the British species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[714,862,1799,1825]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref21228" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplets176 and 179. This complex of species has since been revised (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[508,659,1835,1861]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="211 - 225" refId="ref21370" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2014) Revisionary notes on the Megaselia sulphuripes (Meigen) species group (Dipt., Phoridae). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 150, 211 - 225." type="journal article" year="2014">Disney 2014</bibRefCitation>
). In the revised key to this group it runs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz" authorityName="Schmitz" box="[1151,1350,1835,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="devia">
<emphasis box="[1151,1250,1835,1861]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. devia</emphasis>
Schmitz
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" authorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirticaudata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. hirticaudata</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from both in having the hairs of the abdominal venter restricted to segments 5 and 6, its costal index being less than 0.4, and from 
<taxonomicName box="[665,764,1907,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="devia">
<emphasis box="[665,764,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. devia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having dusky as opposed to yellow palps. In the rest of the world fauna it most closely resembles the Nerarctic 
<taxonomicName authority="Borgmeier (1966)" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1966" box="[736,1104,1943,1970]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaeola">
<emphasis box="[736,896,1943,1969]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. pygmaeola</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier, T." box="[903,1104,1943,1970]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 160" refId="ref20965" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1966) Revision of the North American Phorid flies. Part III. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Megaselia (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, Petropolis, 8, 1 - 160. [1965]" type="journal article" year="1966">Borgmeier (1966)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
but its costal ratios are 4: 1: 1, as opposed to section 2 being clearly longer than 3, and its abdominal tergites are much more sparsely haired.
</paragraph>
